  "prompt": "Does Java support Multiple Inheritance?",
  "response": "Java does **not** support multiple inheritance **with classes**, meaning a single class cannot extend more than one class. This design choice helps avoid complexities and problems such as the \"Diamond Problem,\" where ambiguity arises when two parent classes have methods with the same signature.\n\nHowever, Java **does** support a form of multiple inheritance through **interfaces**. A class can implement multiple interfaces, allowing it to inherit abstract methods from multiple sources. Since Java 8, interfaces can also contain **default methods** (methods with a default implementation), which makes this mechanism even more powerful while still avoiding the issues associated with multiple class inheritance.\n\n### Example of Multiple Inheritance with Interfaces\n\n```java\ninterface InterfaceA {\n    default void sayHello() {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello from InterfaceA\");\n    }\n}\n\ninterface InterfaceB {\n    default void sayHello() {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello from InterfaceB\");\n    }\n}\n\npublic class MyClass implements InterfaceA, InterfaceB {\n    // Must override the conflicting default method\n    @Override\n    public void sayHello() {\n        InterfaceA.super.sayHello(); // Specify which interface's method to use\n        InterfaceB.super.sayHello();\n        System.out.println(\"Hello from MyClass\");\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        MyClass obj = new MyClass();\n        obj.sayHello();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```\nHello from InterfaceA\nHello from InterfaceB\nHello from MyClass\n```\n\nIn this example:\n\n- `MyClass` implements both `InterfaceA` and `InterfaceB`.\n- Both interfaces have a default method `sayHello()`.\n- `MyClass` overrides `sayHello()` to resolve the conflict by specifying which interface's method to use.\n\n### Why Java Restricts Multiple Class Inheritance\n\n1. **Simplicity and Clarity:** Single inheritance keeps the class hierarchy straightforward and more manageable.\n2. **Avoiding Ambiguity:** Multiple inheritance can lead to ambiguities, especially when parent classes have methods with the same signatures.\n3. **Maintenance:** It simplifies the maintenance and evolution of code by reducing the complexity involved in understanding class behaviors.\n\n### Alternatives and Best Practices\n\n- **Use Interfaces:** Leverage interfaces to achieve polymorphism and code reusability without the complications of multiple inheritance.\n- **Composition Over Inheritance:** Favor composing classes with desired behaviors rather than inheriting from multiple classes. This approach enhances flexibility and modularity.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nWhile Java does not allow multiple inheritance through classes to maintain a clear and manageable type hierarchy, it provides the flexibility of achieving similar outcomes through multiple interface implementations. This design balances the need for reusability and flexibility with the principles of simplicity and clarity in object-oriented programming.",
